{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516495"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:43:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:43:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12639"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12639","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12639"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.23,0.5,0,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5120"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75996"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5120","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5120"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12639"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61497"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1890"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8588"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8728"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42790"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44288"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75996","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75996"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department by ambulance with sudden onset severe abdominal pain. He has a known abdominal aortic aneurysm. He collapses in the ambulance and becomes unconscious with profound hypotension. His medical history and medications are unknown. He appears critically unwell with unrecordable blood pressure. A Focused Assessment with Sonography for Trauma (FAST) scan reveals free fluid in the abdomen suggesting active bleeding. He requires immediate surgery for suspected ruptured abdominal aortic aneurysm. No previous blood group and hold results are available.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate combination of blood products for immediate transfusion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["AB positive packed red blood cells and O plasma","O negative packed red blood cells and O plasma","O negative packed red blood cells and AB plasma","AB positive packed red blood cells and AB plasma","O negative whole blood"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient requires immediate transfusion of blood products for suspected ruptured abdominal aortic aneurysm. When the patient\u0027s blood group is unknown and there is insufficient time for blood grouping, universal donor products must be used to avoid potentially fatal transfusion reactions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EO negative packed red blood cells and AB plasma\u003C/strong\u003E is the safest combination. O negative red cells lack A, B and RhD antigens so can be given to any recipient. AB plasma contains no anti-A or anti-B antibodies so can be given to any blood group.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAB positive packed red blood cells and O plasma\u003C/strong\u003E would be dangerous as O plasma contains anti-A and anti-B antibodies that could cause severe transfusion reactions in this patient of unknown blood group.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EO negative packed red blood cells and O plasma\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as O plasma contains anti-A and anti-B antibodies that could cause transfusion reactions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAB positive packed red blood cells and AB plasma\u003C/strong\u003E would be dangerous as AB positive red cells contain A, B and RhD antigens that could trigger severe reactions in patients who are not AB positive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EO negative whole blood\u003C/strong\u003E would provide O negative red cells but the plasma portion would contain anti-A and anti-B antibodies that could cause transfusion reactions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter the immediate emergency is managed and the patient is stabilised, formal blood grouping should be performed to allow type-specific blood products to be used for ongoing transfusion requirements.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["O negative packed red blood cells are the universal donor for red cells as they lack A, B and RhD antigens","AB plasma is the universal donor for plasma as it lacks antibodies to A and B antigens","In emergency situations without blood group information, O negative red cells and AB plasma should be used"],"references":["Blood Groups and Compatibilities [Internet]. The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne; [cited 2023Mar21]. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/bloodtrans/about_blood_products/Blood_Groups_and_Compatibilities/","Ordering blood products [Internet]. The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne; [cited 2023Mar21]. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/bloodtrans/blood_provision/Ordering_Blood_Products/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61497"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12639"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61497","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61497"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T20:52:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T20:57:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"i